This paper focuses on the impact of shilling attacks on recommender systems, which falls under the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. It also analyzes the types of users who are most affected by these attacks, which could fall under the social and information sciences (cs.SI) or human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the fraudulent nature of these attacks, which could fall under the cybersecurity (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents real-world scenarios, which could fall under the social computing (cs.SOC) sub-category.
